<font color="#FF0000">MYTH AND FACT-RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 14 15:54:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Mike:<br>
     Thanks for the understanding.  The Vietnam War is a complex and horrible war.  Today, America needs to discuss what happened in Vietnam and how this country reacted or didn't react.  I understand there will be many emotions surrounding the war, there was back then, there will be know.  My interests in myth and fact are very personal.  My father is a Nam vet and a very decent, successful man.  For his sake and the sake of all other vets, I just don't like to have people believe the wrong information.  How people interpret information is totally up to them, but they need to know the truth.  As a school teacher, I have always tried to do just that, give them the truth and have them interpret it.  There are so many views on this war, one person can't impose their one vision on others, just the truth.  I just wanted to clear that up.  In regards to common knowledge on the war.  The reason I use the term common knowledge to refer to how people in general view the war and the vet, comes from my own experiences.  In college, my colleagues did a survey on the conceptions of the Vietnam War and the Vietnam Vet.  We surveyed school students and members of the general public.  Our results may not have been a precise science, but I was dismayed on how many people had their facts wrong and were basing opinions on this wrong data.  In regards to students, you're right they don't have a conception because they don't know much about it.  All I'm saying is that they deserve the facts and no speculation or interpretation.  Once again, I'll say that this war needs to be discussed and those that were involved with need to be a part of the oral history and study.  In regards to suicide figures on Nam vets Mike, you're right, I too have seen many <br>
numbers and figures from different sources.  My numbers of 9,000 men as a estimate comes from Dr. Houk's testimony to the Congress.  It comes from the Center for Disease Control in Atlanta.  They did extensive study of Vietnam Vets and suicide and came up with that number.<br>
                                              
<p><code>--   (Concerned Teacher) </code><p>


